03926nam a22005895i 9780292794740DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212007txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927947407 a10.7560/7164072doi  a(DE-B1597)588311  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a972/.00049272221 aAlfaro-Velcamp, Theresa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSo Far from Allah, So Close to Mexico :bMiddle Eastern Immigrants in Modern Mexico /cTheresa Alfaro-Velcamp. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (286 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Looking for Antonio Aychur Itt and Finding Hamud Said Eid -- t1. Amplifying Mexicanidad -- t2. Locating Middle Easterners in National and Transnational Histories -- t3. Turco Sojourners Come to Porfirian Mexico -- t4. Borderland Merchants in Revolutionary Mexico -- t5. Middle Eastern Immigrants and Foreigners in Post-Revolutionary Mexico -- t6. Peddling, Positioning, and Prosperity -- t7. Conclusion: Meanings of Multiculturalism -- tAppendix: Tables -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMiddle Eastern immigration to Mexico is one of the intriguing, untold stories in the history of both regions. In So Far from Allah, So Close to Mexico, Theresa Alfaro-Velcamp presents the fascinating findings of her extensive fieldwork in Mexico as well as in Lebanon and Syria, which included comprehensive data collection from more than 8,000 original immigration cards as well as studies of decades of legal publications and the collection of historiographies from descendents of Middle Eastern immigrants living in Mexico today. Adding an important chapter to studies of the Arab diaspora, Alfaro-Velcamp's study shows that political instability in both Mexico and the Middle East kept many from fulfilling their dreams of returning to their countries of origin after realizing wealth in Mexico, in a few cases drawing on an imagined Phoenician past to create a class of economically powerful Lebanese Mexicans. She also explores the repercussions of xenophobia in Mexico, the effect of religious differences, and the impact of key events such as the Mexican Revolution. Challenging the post-revolutionary definitions of mexicanidad and exposing new aspects of the often contradictory attitudes of Mexicans toward foreigners, So Far from Allah, So Close to Mexico should spark timely dialogues regarding race and ethnicity, and the essence of Mexican citizenship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/71640740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292794740423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292794740/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK